\import{base-macros}

\taxon{Blog}

\title{Understanding recursors with Lean4}

\subtree{
  \title{The recursor for natural numbers}
  \p{
    Before we define recursors, let's first introduce the idea of an inductive type. We'll do this by examining how lean defines natural numbers.
  }

  \codeblock{lean}{
    inductive Nat where
    | zero : Nat
    | succ (n : Nat) : Nat
}

  \p{
    The idea here being that we can construct natural numbers by either using the constructor \code{zero} to get \code{0}, or by applying the constructor \code{succ} to an existing natural number to get its successor. For example, we can construct \code{3} as follows:
  }

  \codeblock{lean}{
    def three : Nat := Nat.succ (Nat.succ (Nat.succ Nat.zero))
  }

  \p{
    We can equivalently express this definition using the type formation and term introduction rules:
  }
}
